 {"id": "franken_networkx-flowinf", "title": "REVIEW: [CRITICAL] maximum_flow / maximum_flow_value silently undervalued graphs with uncapacitated edges", "description": "The Rust max-flow residual network treated missing or +inf edge capacity as effectively 1 (or 0). On the most minimal case, s->a (cap=5) -> t (no capacity) fnx returned 1 instead of 5; on nx's own max_flow_min_cost docstring example (12 edges with two uncapacitated) fnx returned max_flow=23 vs nx=28. Added _flow_has_infinite_capacity(flowG, capacity) helper; when it trips, both maximum_flow and maximum_flow_value route through _call_networkx_for_parity, so inf-capacity inputs match nx's answer exactly. Finite-capacity graphs still go through the Rust fast path.", "status": "closed", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx when any edge has non-finite capacity", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-mfmcsign", "title": "REVIEW: [CRITICAL] max_flow_min_cost set demand signs BACKWARDS (source=+maxFlow, sink=-maxFlow); algorithm raised NetworkXUnfeasible on valid input", "description": "By nx convention a negative demand means the node supplies that much flow. fnx.max_flow_min_cost called set_node_attributes(H, {s: max_val, t: -max_val}) \u2014 reversed \u2014 so the downstream min_cost_flow solver was asked to push from t to s and raised NetworkXUnfeasible('no flow satisfies all node demands') on every valid graph. Fixed to use {s: -max_val, t: max_val} per nx, and verified on the nx docstring example (1->7) that fnx now matches nx's optimal cost.", "status": "closed", "priority": 1, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Flip signs per nx convention", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-mcfint", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] min_cost_flow / min_cost_flow_cost / network_simplex / cost_of_flow returned floats for all-int inputs", "description": "nx preserves int flow values when every demand, capacity, and weight on the input graph is an integer (no float(...) casts on the int branch). fnx's Python implementations coerced through float(), so {'s': {'a': 3}} in, {'s': {'a': 3.0}} out; costs came back 9.0 vs nx's 9. Added _mcf_inputs_all_integral(G, demand, capacity, weight) and _coerce_flow_dict_to_int helpers; after min_cost_flow finishes, coerce the flow dict back to int when inputs were all int. Also changed cost_of_flow to initialize total=0 and skip the float() cast on per-edge weight so int+int stays int. Verified fnx now matches nx int-for-int on simple and multi-hop examples, and still returns floats when inputs are floats.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:30:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Int-preserving coercion helpers", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-isplanarbroken", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] is_planar classified K3,3 and Petersen as planar (both are canonical non-planar graphs)", "description": "fnx's _raw_is_planar Rust binding returned True for K3,3 and the Petersen graph \u2014 two textbook non-planar graphs (K3,3 is one of the two Kuratowski forbidden minors). Critically, fnx's own check_planarity already returned the correct (False, None) for the same inputs, so the two functions publicly contradicted each other. Route is_planar through check_planarity so the answer is consistent and matches nx's reference LR-planarity implementation. Verified on K3/K4/K5/K6/K3,3/C5/petersen/star/wheel.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to check_planarity for consistency", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-mixmap", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] degree_mixing_matrix / attribute_mixing_matrix default mapping missed inner-only keys AND differed from nx ordering", "description": "When ``mapping=None``, fnx built the default ordering from ``list(mixing)``, i.e. the outer dict's insertion order. This (a) skipped degree/attribute values that only appeared as *neighbor* endpoints (inner-dict keys), silently dropping matrix rows/cols, and (b) left the rows/cols in a different order than nx. Fix: match nx.utils.misc._dict_to_numpy_array2 by taking the set union of outer + inner keys. On a 4-node graph with edges (0,1)(1,2)(2,3)(0,2) fnx used to return [[2,2,0],[2,0,1],[0,1,0]] (ordering [2,3,1]) vs nx's [[0,0,1],[0,2,2],[1,2,0]] (ordering [1,2,3]); now matches nx exactly.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Set-union default mapping", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-degnbnview", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] Graph.degree(nbunch) returned list of tuples; nx returns DegreeView supporting key indexing", "description": "nx.Graph.degree(nbunch) returns a DegreeView-like object that iterates as (node, degree) tuples AND supports ``view[node]`` key lookup. The Rust DegreeView's __call__(list) returned a plain list, so ``G.degree([0,1])[0]`` returned the tuple ``(0, 1)`` rather than the scalar degree. This broke nx.algorithms.bipartite.degrees (which does ``B.degree(top, weight)`` then ``deg[node]``) plus any caller that mixes iteration with key-indexing. Added _FilteredDegreeView proxy class that implements __iter__, __getitem__, __contains__, __len__, and __call__ for weighted + unweighted restricted views. Verified against bipartite.degrees: ``deg[node]`` now returns the scalar and iteration still yields tuples.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Proxy class with DegreeView contract", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
